WEBVTT

00:08.980 --> 00:13.080
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:29.280 --> 00:34.760
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:37.760 --> 00:39.240
And here are your hosts.

00:44.740 --> 00:45.860
This is Daryl Lane.

00:46.080 --> 00:46.860
And David Cruz.

00:47.440 --> 00:51.400
Some of the most exciting science fiction being written today comes from the Pan of Jack Chalker.

00:51.900 --> 00:57.160
And it's clear that he's a popular writer too, probably best known for the five books in the Well World series.

00:57.660 --> 01:02.260
In fact, the first novel in that series, Midnight at the Well of Souls, has sold over a million copies.

01:02.900 --> 01:08.400
Chalker's first book came out not that long ago, 1976, so his work is still fairly recent.

01:08.700 --> 01:21.820
He'd been active in the field, though, years before he started writing, corresponding with authors and other fans, attending conventions, editing a fanzine, even starting a small publishing company, Mirage Press, to produce material on science fiction.

01:22.400 --> 01:24.800
But Chalker says he'd always planned on being a writer.

01:26.220 --> 01:28.260
I'd always known I was going to be a writer.

01:28.700 --> 01:30.760
I mean, there just was never any question in my mind.

01:31.380 --> 01:34.440
But it was just sort of something that you never really sat down and did.

01:34.560 --> 01:36.920
I used to play around with stories here and there.

01:38.260 --> 01:39.860
John Campbell was a big help.

01:41.960 --> 01:49.680
During the 60s, I would float ideas and fragments off him, and he would be very, very nice and tell me exactly what was wrong.

01:49.680 --> 02:01.440
Of course, what had created everybody about John Campbell was that the man had been editing for 40 years, and he could put his finger on something and tell you exactly what you were doing wrong.

02:02.000 --> 02:06.220
And it was terribly infuriating to discover that he was right in almost every case.

02:07.440 --> 02:10.720
He saw why he did it from 39 until he died.

02:12.540 --> 02:30.400
And as a result of being able to have the help of people like Campbell and August Arilith and a lot of really established writers and editors in the field, I was able to get a good recognition of exactly what was required in the field.

02:31.500 --> 02:34.220
It just was a matter of sitting down and doing it.

02:35.300 --> 02:39.940
And fortunately, he did sit down and do it, publishing Jungle of Stars in 1976.

02:41.580 --> 02:50.120
So I sat on a typewriter, and there was really no question in my mind as to what I'd do first.

02:51.900 --> 02:55.780
I had been playing around with an idea for years and years and years.

02:56.660 --> 03:04.200
There's even a short, fancy version of it, 20 years old, called Jungle or Jungle of Stars.

03:05.320 --> 03:08.400
There were a lot of codewords, but Jungle was always in it.

03:09.620 --> 03:13.340
And I sat down and wrote the things.

03:13.860 --> 03:25.280
I'd been around so long in my mind and in discussions and so on that there were just no problems, no resistance, no having to think it out or anything else.

03:26.300 --> 03:29.420
And I wrote it solidly in about two and a half, three weeks.

03:31.200 --> 03:32.900
And then sent it off.

03:34.400 --> 03:38.320
And it's a good old-fashioned type.

03:39.240 --> 03:42.360
It's a science fiction murder mystery.

03:43.900 --> 03:49.120
Very much at home in the old, astounding analogs and so on.

03:49.120 --> 03:51.960
Even though I thought that's a modern touch to it.

03:57.780 --> 04:01.780
Some of his earlier contacts with people in the field of science fiction paid off.

04:02.040 --> 04:04.300
One of them, Judy Lindell Ray, bought the novel.

04:05.760 --> 04:19.840
Judy Lindell Ray, who had just become editor of Ballantine, which was soon to have a science fiction line named after her, took a look at it.

04:19.840 --> 04:22.380
We'd known each other for about 15 years.

04:23.740 --> 04:33.180
And she put off reading it for quite a long time because she was afraid that if it was terrible and she said so, that she'd blow our friendship or something.

04:33.900 --> 04:39.920
Finally, she said, we got together at a convention and she admitted to me all this.

04:40.120 --> 04:41.860
She said, okay, I'll read it, but be prepared.

04:42.540 --> 04:47.440
And about four days later, I get a phone call and she said, hey, this is great. I want to buy it.

04:48.820 --> 04:50.400
And that was the first sale.

04:52.080 --> 04:55.960
Since then, Chalker has published some 13 novels and he's still going strong.

04:56.660 --> 04:58.260
More with Jack Chalker next time.

