12:27.600 --> 12:32.080
The five novels in Jack Chalker's Well World series are based on a familiar science fiction concept.

12:32.080 --> 12:38.180
And that concept is the notion of a long dead race of superior beings whose artifacts are found by humans.

12:38.520 --> 12:42.520
But there are a couple of interesting twists given to this concept by Chalker.

12:43.220 --> 12:45.960
One twist is the principal artifact by the vanished race.

12:46.420 --> 12:48.340
It's a planet called the Well World.

12:48.860 --> 12:54.720
It's artificial and its interior is a super computer that can transform matter into all sorts of living creatures.

12:54.720 --> 13:01.920
It's really a laboratory planet where species are created and tested before being transferred to various places throughout the universe.

13:02.360 --> 13:07.480
And the other twist is that the superior beings, called the Markovians, aren't actually gone.

13:08.160 --> 13:10.860
They just transformed themselves into other, more primitive beings.

13:11.500 --> 13:13.280
Chalker talks about the Markovians.

13:14.040 --> 13:23.380
They got to the point where they were gone, literally, where their devices could conjure up anything they wanted, just with a mere thought of it.

13:25.120 --> 13:34.860
I sense that it pointed out to me that they're sort of like the Crel in the old movie Forbidden Planet, and that they reached this Godhead status.

13:35.580 --> 13:41.200
But the Crel experiments failed because they couldn't control their passions.

13:42.160 --> 13:47.420
And the Markovian experiments succeeded and they literally became gods and they became miserable.

13:47.420 --> 13:51.820
There was nothing left to attain. There was nothing left to know.

13:53.000 --> 14:01.540
You had a bunch of creatures that spent millions of years rising to this point and they sit around and they say, is this all there is?

14:03.100 --> 14:05.980
At this point, the Markovians decided to start all over again.

14:06.800 --> 14:25.500
The idea of the great experiment came about was to redo it, to literally start the Markovians over from scratch with different kinds of creatures, different environments, with no real value system.

14:25.780 --> 14:29.360
I mean, they have to develop their own unique value systems. They do.

14:30.260 --> 14:36.820
And as a result, they're grown and they're tested on this laboratory world, the well world.

14:37.280 --> 14:48.320
And then they were the ones that worked, the ones that showed promise of survival, were then set into motion out throughout the universe, including man.

14:50.940 --> 15:03.560
And they had the hope that eventually one of these races would reach a state of perfection that would not be empty or hollow.

15:04.600 --> 15:10.620
Now, I personally believe that when you reach that state, it is empty and hollow.

15:11.360 --> 15:19.880
But that's just my feeling other people might certainly do think differently.

15:21.900 --> 15:26.800
The Markovians create hundreds of different species, all intelligent, but all incredibly different.

15:27.240 --> 15:30.780
We asked Tucker how he gets ideas for creating such a variety of aliens.

15:32.320 --> 15:44.040
I used a variety of things. In some cases, a good pictorial natural history text will give you more weird creatures than you've ever seen, which can be modified.

15:45.820 --> 15:54.320
Some came out of mythology. Some came more or less direct out of Fantasia, sorts of like that.

15:55.020 --> 15:59.580
And a few came out of comic book concepts.

16:01.020 --> 16:06.340
You just draw them in from all over and you use basic shapes and basic types.

16:07.260 --> 16:14.700
And then you adjust them to what would happen if these were real, convenient, intelligent creatures.

16:16.300 --> 16:23.120
I found very, very little trouble in coming up with an enormous variety of them.

16:23.780 --> 16:29.480
I'm not sure whether I could come up with 1,560, which is the number I would have to to visit every hex in the world.

16:30.360 --> 16:33.240
But I've had no trouble coming up with the 2,300 so far.

