19:07.380 --> 19:14.120
I had so much correspondence, I can't believe how many people I was contacting on a regular basis.

19:14.120 --> 19:29.900
And so I started tapping them and created the fanzine Mirage, in addition to a $40 surplus mini-graph found in an old store, which I still own, by the way, and which still works.

19:31.780 --> 19:35.560
I was able to start putting out a fanzine called Mirage.

19:36.720 --> 19:42.640
The fanzine was successful because of its high quality, and it led into a small publishing company, Mirage Press.

19:44.400 --> 19:50.620
I was serious and constructive at the same time that everybody else was being just sort of kid hobbyist.

19:51.120 --> 20:01.560
I really had a magazine that discussed the literature, discussed the writers and so on past and present, and a time when very few of these were coming out.

20:02.200 --> 20:08.420
And so I attracted a rather large audience of collectors and professional writers and artists and so on.

20:08.420 --> 20:27.040
And I was able to create out of that the Mirage Press, which started off, again, as mini-graphed publications and then later grew as capital grew into a hardcover and paperback, quality paperback publishing house.

20:29.100 --> 20:32.440
Chalker says that Mirage Press was successful from the start.

20:33.600 --> 20:38.000
I started off with a bibliography of H.P. Lovecraft, which I did myself.

20:39.020 --> 21:00.220
Put it together, mini-graphed it with the help of Auguste Aralind, who owned the rights to the H.P. Lovecraft material at the time, and sold it for what in 1960 was a horrendous fee of a $1.

21:00.220 --> 21:03.080
And we sold a hundred of them.

21:05.040 --> 21:09.820
Mirage Press publishes non-fiction materials such as bibliographies and critical studies of authors.

21:10.640 --> 21:12.960
Chalker leaves the publishing of fiction to the large companies.

21:14.200 --> 21:20.380
You can't compete with double-dates, I'm a chooster and so on, for the good stuff in fiction.

21:21.200 --> 21:35.100
And although I did do a little bit of fiction, getting into prints and books of work that I thought was very, very neglected, you really have to promote fiction.

21:36.240 --> 21:44.060
Whereas non-fiction and reference material is always, there's always a heavy market and there's been a growing market for it.

21:44.600 --> 21:46.800
And so I concentrated in that end.

21:47.620 --> 21:58.380
And we came up with some rather successful books, Guide to Middle-Earth, which in its Valentine's form, which I still own a piece of, is still selling well on Atlas of Fantasy.

22:01.900 --> 22:06.920
We did three books on sword and sorcery fiction before the comic books discovered Conan.

22:08.880 --> 22:22.360
And occasionally we did rather odd materials such as a collection of all of the Ferdinand fake hoot, bad puns that have been published over the years, this kind of thing.

22:23.460 --> 22:28.680
Mostly though we were serious reference works and we still have a number of them that are standard.

